item.title: South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol faces investigation amid martial law controversy
item.description: South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol faces an impeachment vote following his controversial attempt to impose martial law. Accusations of treason against Yoon and top officials are under investigation by police, spurred by an opposition complaint. The move to declare martial law, which included deploying troops to parliament, sparked public outrage and international concern.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Hawk Tuah Girl’s $HAWK Meme Coin crashes minutes after launch
item.description: The $HAWK debacle highlights the inherent risks of investing in meme coins, which are often driven by speculative behavior and subject to extreme volatility. The incident has drawn sharp criticism online, with many calling for stricter oversight of cryptocurrency projects to prevent such outcomes in the future.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Watch: This German engineer's underwater home has a bed, toilet, TV, computer, clocks, internet and more
item.description: German aerospace engineer, Rudiger Koch, is currently living 36 feet underwater off Panama's coast in a submersible capsule. He aims to spend 120 days submerged, breaking the current record. Koch's experiment explores the ocean's potential for human habitation, advocating for ocean-based communities. His capsule provides basic amenities, and he's monitored for health and safety.
item.dc:creator: TOI Science Desk

item.title: 'No burgers, soft drinks and burgers': UK bans daytime TV ads for junk food in bid to tackle child obesity
item.description: The UK government will introduce a 9 pm watershed ban on TV adverts for unhealthy foods high in sugar, fat, and salt, starting October next year. This measure aims to combat rising childhood obesity rates, impacting products like granola, muffins, and pastries, but excluding general fast-food chain advertising.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: No Russian oil flowing through Druzhba pipeline to Czech Republic, Unipetrol says
item.description: Russian oil flows to the Czech Republic via the Druzhba pipeline have been mysteriously halted, leaving Czech refiner Unipetrol relying on reserves. While officials assure the public fuel supplies remain unaffected, the stoppage's cause is still under investigation.

item.title: The troubled history of South Korean presidents
item.description: South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol faces impeachment after a controversial move to suspend civilian rule. This follows a pattern of tumultuous presidential tenures marked by corruption, scandal, and even suicide. Previous leaders like Park Geun-hye and Lee Myung-bak were jailed for corruption, while Roh Moo-hyun tragically took his own life amid investigations.

item.title: Ukraine imposes sanctions on Ivanishvili, some members of Georgia government
item.description: Ukraine's President sanctioned Georgia's former Prime Minister and officials. Zelenskiy accused them of pro-Russian leanings. Georgia's governing party faces accusations of authoritarianism. Tensions escalated after Georgia suspended EU accession talks. Protests and clashes with police followed. Zelenskiy urged international action against Georgia's government.

item.title: Why Amazon's founder Jeff Bezos is very optimistic about Trump 2.0?
item.description: Jeff Bezos expressed optimism about the Trump administration, citing potential deregulation benefits. He defended his decision against The Washington Post endorsing candidates and aimed to dispel Trump's perceived media hostility. Bezos also downplayed concerns about Elon Musk's influence on regulatory reforms impacting their space ventures.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Tens of thousands of hours of footage': How cops plan to hunt down Brian Thompson's killer
item.description: In a brazen Manhattan shooting, UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson was killed Wednesday morning. The NYPD is leveraging its extensive surveillance network, including footage from public and private cameras, to track the skilled gunman who fled into Central Park. Despite capturing the suspect's movements, his identity and motive remain unknown, highlighting the challenges of even the most sophisticated surveillance systems.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Detectives uncover new evidences in Brian Thompson's murder case
item.description: A masked gunman shot and killed UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson outside a Hilton hotel in Manhattan. Shell casings inscribed with "deny," "defend," and "depose" were found at the scene. The assailant fled on an e-bike into Central Park, and police are searching for a potential witness seen fleeing the scene.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Isro begins revised countdown for Proba-3 mission launch
item.description: Isro launched ESA's Proba-3 mission on December 5th, after a delay due to a propulsion system anomaly. The two satellites will study the Sun's corona by flying in precise formation, a key demonstration for future missions. This marks ESA's return to launching with Isro after 23 years and follows Isro's recent Aditya-L1 solar mission.
item.dc:creator: TOI Science Desk

item.title: Ex-defence chief suggested martial law to President Yoon, says South Korean interior minister
item.description: South Korean Defense Minister Kim Yong-hyun resigned after allegedly suggesting martial law to President Yoon Suk Yeol. President Yoon declared martial law, citing North Korean threats, and deployed troops to parliament. An impeachment motion against Yoon is scheduled for a parliamentary vote on Saturday. Choi Byung-huk has been selected as the new defense minister.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Nearly 12 Vietnamese soldiers killed during military exercise
item.description: Tragedy struck a Vietnamese military training exercise in Dong Nai province when an accidental explosion claimed the lives of twelve soldiers. The incident occurred Monday night during a severe storm, reportedly when a lightning strike triggered an electronic detonator while the soldiers were transporting explosives. Recovery efforts are underway, and the Ministry of Defence has launched an urgent investigation.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Are Prince Harry and Meghan Markle planning to stay in US forever? Here is the answer
item.description: Prince Harry expressed contentment with his US life, emphasizing the freedom to engage in activities with his children that wouldn't be possible in the UK. While Harry spoke at a New York summit, Meghan sent holiday greetings from a London charity event. The couple's separate appearances fuel ongoing divorce rumors.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: French twist: Macron’s premier ousted in no-trust vote. What's next
item.description: French Prime Minister Michel Barnier's government was ousted after a no-confidence vote spurred by a budget dispute. The far-right and left joined forces to oppose Barnier's proposed budget cuts and tax increases. President Macron now faces the challenge of appointing a new prime minister who can navigate a deeply divided parliament and address France's economic woes.

item.title: US President-elect Donald Trump nominates former congressman Billy Long as IRS commissioner
item.description: Former Missouri Congressman Billy Long has been nominated by President-elect Trump to lead the IRS, replacing current commissioner Daniel Werfel. This move comes amidst Republican opposition to the Biden administration's IRS funding increases. Long, known for his auctioneering background, will require Senate confirmation for the position.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Manhunt underway for killer of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson after fatal shooting
item.description: UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson, 50, was shot and killed outside a Hilton hotel in Manhattan. A masked gunman fired repeatedly after an apparent gun malfunction, then fled on a Citi Bike. Police are investigating the incident, analyzing surveillance footage, and exploring potential motives, including workplace connections.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Biden administration weighs preemptive pardons for Fauci, Schiff, and other ahead of Trump return
item.description: White House officials are debating preemptive pardons for individuals like Dr. Anthony Fauci, Adam Schiff, and Liz Cheney, anticipating potential prosecution under a returning Trump administration. This follows Trump's selection of Kash Patel as FBI lead and concerns about retribution against perceived critics. The discussions consider the implications of such pardons and the financial burdens of potential legal defenses.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: California school shooting: Two children hospitalised, suspected gunman dead
item.description: Two children were shot at Feather River School of Seventh-Day Adventists in Oroville, California, after a gunman opened fire on Wednesday. The shooter later died by suicide. The injured students were transported to hospitals, and their conditions remain unknown. Authorities believe the shooter had no connection to the school. Students were reunited with their families at a nearby church.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
